        <bioghist>
            <p>Barbara Sapinsley’s book The Private War of Mrs. Packard: The Dramatic Story of a Nineteenth-Century Feminist was published in 1991 by Paragon House. It includes a foreword by Dr. Eric T. Carlson, the former director of the DeWitt Wallace Institute of Psychiatry. The subject of the book is Elizabeth Ware Packard, and the cover of the book describes it as “the dramatic story of the 19th century feminist who lobbied for laws to protect wives from husbands who could commit them to mental institutions without legitimate cause.” </p>
        </bioghist>
